                   =20
                    <section aria-labelledby=3D"Abs1" data-title=3D"Abstrac=
t" lang=3D"en"><div class=3D"c-article-section" id=3D"Abs1-section"><h2 cla=
ss=3D"c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sect=
ions-item" id=3D"Abs1">Abstract</h2><div class=3D"c-article-section__conten=
t" id=3D"Abs1-content"><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading" data-test=3D"ab=
stract-sub-heading">Background</h3><p>A frequently used statistic for testi=
ng homogeneity in a meta-analysis of <i>K</i> independent studies is Cochra=
n=E2=80=99s <i>Q</i>. For a standard test of homogeneity the <i>Q</i> stati=
stic is referred to a chi-square distribution with <i>K</i>=E2=88=921 degre=
es of freedom. For the situation in which the effects of the studies are lo=
garithms of odds ratios, the chi-square distribution is much too conservati=
ve for moderate size studies, although it may be asymptotically correct as =
the individual studies become large.</p><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading=
" data-test=3D"abstract-sub-heading">Methods</h3><p>Using a mixture of theo=
retical results and simulations, we provide formulas to estimate the shape =
and scale parameters of a gamma distribution to fit the distribution of <i>=
Q</i>.</p><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading" data-test=3D"abstract-sub-he=
ading">Results</h3><p>Simulation studies show that the gamma distribution i=
s a good approximation to the distribution for <i>Q</i>.</p><h3 class=3D"c-=
article__sub-heading" data-test=3D"abstract-sub-heading">Conclusions</h3><p=
>Use of the gamma distribution instead of the chi-square distribution for <=
i>Q</i> should eliminate inaccurate inferences in assessing homogeneity in =
a meta-analysis. (A computer program for implementing this test is provided=
.) This hypothesis test is competitive with the Breslow-Day test both in ac=
curacy of level and in power.</p></div></div></section>

