                                <div class=3D"main-content">
                                    <section data-title=3D"Background"><div=
 class=3D"c-article-section" id=3D"Sec1-section"><h2 class=3D"c-article-sec=
tion__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id=3D"Se=
c1">Background</h2><div class=3D"c-article-section__content" id=3D"Sec1-con=
tent"><p>The combination of the results of several similar studies has many=
 applications in statistical practice, notably in the meta-analysis of medi=
cal and social science studies and also in multi-center medical trials. An =
important first step in such a combination is to decide whether the several=
 studies are sufficiently similar. This decision is often accomplished via =
a so-called test of homogeneity. The outcomes of the studies may be express=
ed in a variety of effect measures, such as: sample means; odds ratios, rel=
ative risks or risk differences arising from 2=C3=972 tables; standardized =
mean differences of two arms of the studies; and many more. A variety of st=
atistics for use in tests of homogeneity have been proposed; some are speci=
fic to the type of effect measure, and some are applicable to several measu=
res.</p><p>This paper has its main focus on the test statistic first introd=
uced by Cochran [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anc=
hor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Ref=
erence 1" title=3D"Cochran WG. Problems arising in the analysis of a series=
 of similar experiments. J R Stat Soc Suppl. 1937; 4:102=E2=80=9319." href=
=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR1" id=
=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e434">1</a>] and [<a data-track=3D"click" dat=
a-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"=
citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 2" title=3D"Cochran WG. The combinati=
on of estimates from different experiments. Biometrics. 1954; 10:101=E2=80=
=9329." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x=
#ref-CR2" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e437">2</a>] and its application =
to testing homogeneity when the effects of interest are odds ratios arising=
 from experiments with dichotomous outcomes in treatment and control arms. =
Cochran=E2=80=99s <i>Q</i> statistic is defined by <span class=3D"mathjax-t=
ex">\(Q=3D\sum _{i} \widehat {w}_{i}(\widehat {\theta }_{i}-\widehat {\thet=
a }_{w})^{2}\)</span> where <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta =
}_{i}\)</span> is the effect estimator of the <i>i</i>th study, <span class=
=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta }_{w} =3D\sum _{i}\widehat {w}_{i}\wide=
hat {\theta }_{i}/\sum _{i}\widehat {w}_{i}\)</span> is the weighted averag=
e of the estimators of the effects, and the weight <span class=3D"mathjax-t=
ex">\(\widehat {w}_{i}\)</span> is the inverse of the variance estimator of=
 <i>i</i>th effect estimator. The use of inverse variance weights has the a=
ppealing feature of weighting larger and more accurate studies more heavily=
 in the weighted mean <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta }_{w}\=
)</span> and in the statistic <i>Q</i>. This statistic was investigated for=
 the case that the study effects are normally distributed sample means by C=
ochran and also by Welch [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"refe=
rence anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-lab=
el=3D"Reference 3" title=3D"Welch BL. On the comparison of several mean val=
ues: an alternative approach. Biometrika. 1951; 38:330=E2=80=936." href=3D"=
https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR3" id=3D"=
ref-link-section-d57159360e814">3</a>] and James [<a data-track=3D"click" d=
ata-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=
=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 4" title=3D"James GS. The compari=
son of several groups of observations when the ratios of the population var=
iances are unknown. Biometrika. 1951; 38:324=E2=80=939." href=3D"https://li=
nk.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR4" id=3D"ref-link-s=
ection-d57159360e817">4</a>]. Perhaps the first application of the <i>Q</i>=
 statistic to testing homogeneity of the logarithm of odds ratios is due to=
 Woolf in 1955 [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anch=
or" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Refe=
rence 5" title=3D"Woolf B. On estimating the relation between blood group a=
nd disease. Ann Human Genet. 1955; 19:251=E2=80=933." href=3D"https://link.=
springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR5" id=3D"ref-link-sect=
ion-d57159360e823">5</a>]. DerSimonian and Laird [<a data-track=3D"click" d=
ata-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=
=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 6" title=3D"DerSimonian R, Laird =
N. Meta-analysis in clinical trials. Controlled Clin Trials. 1986; 7:177=E2=
=80=9388." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-003=
4-x#ref-CR6" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e826">6</a>] extended the use =
of <i>Q</i> for studies with binomial outcomes to difference of proportions=
 as well as to log odds ratios in the context of the random effects model i=
n which the studies are assumed to be sampled from a hypothetical populatio=
n of potential studies. However, the use of <i>Q</i> in a test of homogenei=
ty is the same whether a random effects or fixed effects model is used.</p>=
<p>Under fairly general conditions, in the absence of heterogeneity, <i>Q</=
i> will follow asymptotically (as the individual studies become large) the =
chi-square distribution with <i>K</i>=E2=88=921 degrees of freedom where <i=
>K</i> is the number of studies. It is common practice to assume that <i>Q<=
/i> has this null distribution, regardless of the sizes of the individual s=
tudies or the effect measure. But this null distribution is inaccurate (exc=
ept asymptotically), and its use causes inferences based on <i>Q</i> to be =
inaccurate. This conclusion of inaccuracy should also apply to inferences b=
ased on any statistics which are derived from <i>Q</i>, such as the <i>I</i=
>
                        <sup>2</sup> statistic (see [<a data-track=3D"click=
" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-tes=
t=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 7" title=3D"Higgins JPT, Thompso=
n SG. Quantifying heterogeneity in meta-analysis. Stat Med. 2002; 21:1531=
=E2=80=9358." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-=
0034-x#ref-CR7" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e863">7</a>] and [<a data-t=
rack=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"l=
ink" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 8" title=3D"Huedo-M=
edina TB, S=C3=A1nchez-Meca J, Mar=C3=ADn-Mart=C3=ADnez F, Botella J. Asses=
sing heterogeneity in meta-analysis: Q statistic or I
                           2 index?Psychol Methods. 2006; 11(2):193=E2=80=
=93206." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-=
x#ref-CR8" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e866">8</a>]). Little is known o=
f a theoretical nature about the null distribution of <i>Q</i> under non-as=
ymptotic conditions. In our previous work, together with Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=
=B8l, we have provided improved approximations to the null distribution of =
<i>Q</i> when the effect measure of interest is the standardized mean diffe=
rence [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-=
track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 9" =
title=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. Testing for ho=
mogeneity in meta-analysis I, The one parameter case: Standardized mean dif=
ference. Biometrics. 2011; 67:203=E2=80=9312. doi:10.1111/j.1541-0420.2010.=
01442.x." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034=
-x#ref-CR9" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e876">9</a>] and the risk diffe=
rence [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-=
track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 10"=
 title=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. On the moment=
s of Cochran=E2=80=99s Q statistic under the null hypothesis, with applicat=
ion to the meta-analysis of risk difference. Res Synth Methods. 2011; 2:254=
=E2=80=9370.=20
                    doi:10.1002/jrsm.54
                   =20
                 =20
                        " href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186=
/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR10" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e879">10</a>].=
 In this paper we use a combination of theoretical and simulation results t=
o estimate the mean and variance of <i>Q</i> when the effects are logarithm=
s of odds ratios. We use these estimated moments to approximate the null di=
stribution of <i>Q</i> by a gamma distribution and then apply that distribu=
tion in a homogeneity test based on <i>Q</i> (to be denoted <i>Q</i>
                        <sub>
                  <i>=CE=B3</i>
                </sub>) that is substantially more accurate than the use of=
 the chi-square distribution. We also compare the accuracy and power of thi=
s test with those of other homogeneity tests, such as that of Breslow and D=
ay [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-tra=
ck-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 11" ti=
tle=3D"Breslow NE, Day NE. Statistical methods in cancer research. Int Agen=
cy Res Cancer. 1980; 1:136=E2=80=9346." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/a=
rticle/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR11" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360=
e901">11</a>]. Briefly, both the accuracy and the power of our test are com=
parable to those of the Breslow-Day test (see Sections=E2=80=9C<a data-trac=
k=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" =
href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec7">A=
ccuracy of the level of the homogeneity test</a>=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C<a d=
ata-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section =
anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x=
#Sec8">Power of the homogeneity test</a>)=E2=80=9D.</p><p>After introducing=
 notation and the main assumptions in Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"cli=
ck" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"=
https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec3">Notation =
and assumptions</a>=E2=80=9D, we proceed to our study of the moments of <i>=
Q</i> for log odds ratios in Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-=
track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://l=
ink.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec4">The mean and varia=
nce of <i>Q</i>
                        </a>=E2=80=9D and to their estimation in Section =
=E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-actio=
n=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s128=
74-015-0034-x#Sec5">Estimating the moments and distribution of <b><i>Q</i><=
/b>
                           <sub>
                    <b><i>LOR</i></b>
                  </sub>
                        </a>=E2=80=9D. Results of our simulations of the ac=
hieved level and power of the standard <i>Q</i> test, the Breslow-Day test =
and the proposed improved test of homogeneity based on <i>Q</i>
                        <sub>
                  <i>=CE=B3</i>
                </sub> are given in Sections =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"clic=
k" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"h=
ttps://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec7">Accuracy o=
f the level of the homogeneity test</a>=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C<a data-track=
=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" h=
ref=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec8">Po=
wer of the homogeneity test</a>=E2=80=9D. Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D=
"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=
=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec9">Examp=
le: a meta-analysis of Stead et al. (2013)</a>=E2=80=9D contains an example=
 from the medical literature to illustrate our results and to compare them =
to other tests. Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=
=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.springe=
r.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec10">Conclusions</a>=E2=80=9D con=
tains a discussion and summary of our conclusions. We provide information o=
n the design of our simulations in the <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-l=
abel=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.spr=
inger.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec11">Appendix</a>; and more r=
esults of the simulations for various sample sizes, including unbalanced de=
signs and unequal effects, are contained in the accompanying =E2=80=98Furth=
er Appendices=E2=80=99, together with additional information about the deri=
vation of our procedures. Our R program for calculation of the <i>Q</i>
                        <sub>
                  <i>=CE=B3</i>
                </sub> test of homogeneity can be downloaded from the Journ=
al website.</p></div></div></section><section data-title=3D"Methods"><div c=
lass=3D"c-article-section" id=3D"Sec2-section"><h2 class=3D"c-article-secti=
on__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id=3D"Sec2=
">Methods</h2><div class=3D"c-article-section__content" id=3D"Sec2-content"=
><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading" id=3D"Sec3">Notation and assumptions<=
/h3><p>We assume that there are <i>K</i> studies each with two arms, which =
we call =E2=80=98treatment=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98control=E2=80=99 and use t=
he subscripts <i>T</i> and <i>C</i>. The sizes of the arms of the <i>i</i>t=
h study are <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub> and <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>; let <i>N</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>=3D<i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub>+<i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub> and let <i>q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>=3D<i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>/<i>N</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>. Data in the arms have binomial distributions with=
 probabilities <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub> and <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>. The effect of interest is the logarithm of the od=
ds ratio <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>=3D log[<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub>/(1=E2=88=92<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub>)]=E2=88=92 log[<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>/(1=E2=88=92<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>)]. The null hypothesis to be tested is the equalit=
y of the odds ratios (or equivalently their logarithms) across the several =
studies, i.e., <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>1</sub>=3D=E2=8B=AF=3D<i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>K</i>
                  </sub>:=3D<i>=CE=B8</i>.</p><p>To estimate <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>, we follow Gart, Pettigrew and Thomas [<a data-tra=
ck=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"lin=
k" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 12" title=3D"Gart JJ,=
 Pettigrew HM, Thomas DG. The effect of bias, variance estimation, skewness=
 and kurtosis of the empirical logit on weighted least squares analysis. Bi=
ometrika. 1985; 72:179=E2=80=9390." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/artic=
le/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR12" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e116=
9">12</a>] who showed that if <i>x</i> successes occur from the binomial di=
stribution <i>B</i>
                           <i>i</i>
                           <i>n</i>(<i>n</i>;<i>p</i>), then among the esti=
mators of log[<i>p</i>/(1=E2=88=92<i>p</i>)] given by <i>L</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>a</i>
                  </sub>(<i>x</i>)=3D log[(<i>x</i>+<i>a</i>)/(<i>n</i>=E2=
=88=92<i>x</i>+<i>a</i>)], the estimator with <i>a</i>=3D1/2 has minimum as=
ymptotic bias; and indeed, this is the only choice of <i>a</i> for which al=
l terms for the bias in the expansion of <i>L</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>a</i>
                  </sub>(<i>x</i>) having order <i>O</i>(1/<i>n</i>) vanish=
. Gart et al. [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference ancho=
r" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Refer=
ence 12" title=3D"Gart JJ, Pettigrew HM, Thomas DG. The effect of bias, var=
iance estimation, skewness and kurtosis of the empirical logit on weighted =
least squares analysis. Biometrika. 1985; 72:179=E2=80=9390." href=3D"https=
://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR12" id=3D"ref-=
link-section-d57159360e1251">12</a>] also show that=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ1" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$ \text{Var}[L_{1/2}]=3D\fr=
ac{1}{np(1-p)}+\frac{(1+2p)^{2}}{2n^{2}p^{2}(1-p)^{2}}+O\left(1/n^{3}\right=
)   $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-article-equation__number">
                    ((1))
                </div></div>
                        <p>and suggest the use of the following unbiased es=
timator of the variance: (<i>x</i>+1/2)<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>+(<i>n</i>=E2=
=88=92<i>x</i>+1/2)<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>. Accordingly, if <i>x</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> and <i>y</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> are the number of successes in the treatment and c=
ontrol arms of the <i>i</i>th study, we estimate <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> by <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta =
}_{i}=3D L_{1/2}(x_{i})-L_{1/2}(y_{i})\)</span>. We estimate the variance o=
f <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta }_{i}\)</span> by=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ2" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$ \begin{aligned} \widehat{=
\text{Var}}[\widehat{\theta}_{i}]=3D&amp;\,\frac{1}{x_{i}+1/2}+ \frac{1}{n_=
{Ti}-x_{i}+1/2}+\frac{1}{y_{i}+1/2}\\&amp;+ \frac{1}{n_{Ci}-y_{i}+1/2}. \en=
d{aligned}   $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-article-equation__number">
                    ((2))
                </div></div>
                        <p>A weight <i>w</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> is assigned to the <i>i</i>th study as the inverse=
 of the variance of <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta }_{i}\)<=
/span>, and the weight is estimated by <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\wideh=
at {w}_{i}=3D\widehat {\text {Var}}[\widehat {\theta }_{i}]^{-1}\)</span>. =
The weighted average of the log odds ratio effects is given by <span class=
=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\theta }_{w}=3D\sum _{i}\widehat {w}_{i}\wideh=
at {\theta }_{i}/\sum _{i}\widehat {w}_{i}\)</span>. Then Cochran=E2=80=99s=
 <i>Q</i> statistic is defined as the weighted sum of the squared deviation=
s of the individual effects from the average; that is,=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ3" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$ Q=3D\sum_{i=3D1}^{K}\wide=
hat{w}_{i}(\widehat{\theta}_{i}-\widehat{\theta}_{w})^{2}.   $$ </span></di=
v><div class=3D"c-article-equation__number">
                    ((3))
                </div></div>
                        <p>The =E2=80=9Cstandard=E2=80=9D version of the <i=
>Q</i> statistic, denoted <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>stand</i>
                  </sub> does not add 1/2 to the number of events in both a=
rms when calculating log-odds unless this is required to define their varia=
nces.</p><p>The distribution of <i>Q</i> under the null hypothesis of equal=
ity of the effects <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> depends on the value of the common effect <i>=CE=
=B8</i>, the number of studies <i>K</i> and the sample sizes <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ti</i>
                  </sub> and <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>. However additional information is needed to speci=
fy a unique distribution for <i>Q</i>. For example, the common effect <i>=
=CE=B8</i>=3D0 (that is, the probabilities for the treatment and control ar=
ms are equal), could arise with all probabilities equal to 1/2 (in both arm=
s of all studies) or with some of the studies having probabilities of 1/4 i=
n both arms and others having probabilities of 1/3 in both arms. To uniquel=
y specify a distribution for <i>Q</i>, we need to introduce a =E2=80=98nuis=
ance=E2=80=99 parameter <i>=CE=B6</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub> for each study. It is convenient to take <i>=CE=B6=
</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>i</i>
                  </sub>=3D log[<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>/(1=E2=88=92<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>)] to be the log odds for the control arm of the <i=
>i</i>th study and to estimate it as described above, i.e., <span class=3D"=
mathjax-tex">\(\widehat {\zeta }_{i}=3DL_{1/2}(y_{i})\)</span>.</p><h3 clas=
s=3D"c-article__sub-heading" id=3D"Sec4">The mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                        </h3><p>The <i>Q</i> statistic has long been known =
to behave asymptotically, as the sample sizes become large, as a chi-square=
 distributed random variable with mean <i>K</i>=E2=88=921 and variance, whi=
ch is necessarily twice the mean, 2(<i>K</i>=E2=88=921). However, the choic=
e of effect (e.g., log odds ratio, sample mean, standardized mean differenc=
e) has a substantial impact on the distribution of <i>Q</i> for small to mo=
derate sample sizes, which in turn affects the use of <i>Q</i> as a statist=
ic for a test of homogeneity. For this section, we shall use the notation <=
i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>SM</i>
                  </sub> for <i>Q</i> when the effect is a normally distrib=
uted sample mean and <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> when the effect is the logarithm of the odds ratio=
.</p><p>Assuming that the data from the studies are distributed <span class=
=3D"mathjax-tex">\(N(\mu,{\sigma _{i}^{2}})\)</span>, Welch [<a data-track=
=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link"=
 data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 3" title=3D"Welch BL. O=
n the comparison of several mean values: an alternative approach. Biometrik=
a. 1951; 38:330=E2=80=936." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.11=
86/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR3" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e2563">3</a>]=
 and James [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" =
data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Referenc=
e 4" title=3D"James GS. The comparison of several groups of observations wh=
en the ratios of the population variances are unknown. Biometrika. 1951; 38=
:324=E2=80=939." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-0=
15-0034-x#ref-CR4" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e2566">4</a>] first stud=
ied the moments of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>SM</i>
                  </sub> under the null hypothesis of homogeneity; using th=
e normality properties, they calculated asymptotic expansions for the mean =
and variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>SM</i>
                  </sub>, and Welch matched these moments to those of a re-=
scaled F-distribution to create a homogeneity test now known as the Welch t=
est. It is useful, for comparison with <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>, to examine Welch=E2=80=99s mean and variance for =
<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>SM</i>
                  </sub>. Omitting terms of order <span class=3D"mathjax-te=
x">\(1/{n_{i}^{2}}\)</span> and smaller, Welch found=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ4" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$\begin{array}{@{}rcl@{}} \=
text{E}[Q_{SM}]=3D(K-1)+ 2\sum\frac{1-1/\left(W{\sigma_{i}^{2}}\right)}{n_{=
i}-1} \end{array} $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-article-equation__number"=
>
                    ((4))
                </div></div>
                       =20
                  <div id=3D"Equ5" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=
=3D"c-article-equation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$\begin{arra=
y}{@{}rcl@{}}  \text{Var}[Q_{SM}] =3D 2(K-1)+14\sum\frac{1-1/\left(W{\sigma=
_{i}^{2}}\right)}{n_{i}-1} \end{array} $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-arti=
cle-equation__number">
                    ((5))
                </div></div>
                <p>where <i>W</i> is the sum of the =E2=80=9Ctheoretical=E2=
=80=9D weights <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(n_{i}/{\sigma _{i}^{2}}\)</spa=
n>. Notice the following facts about these moments. 1) They converge to the=
 chi-square moments as the sample sizes increase. 2) Both moments are large=
r than the corresponding chi-square moments. We shall call the difference b=
etween the moments of <i>Q</i> and the corresponding chi-square moments: =
=E2=80=98corrections=E2=80=99. 3) The variance is more than twice the mean.=
 4) The moments depend on the nuisance parameters <span class=3D"mathjax-te=
x">\({\sigma _{i}^{2}}\)</span>, which are estimated independently of the e=
ffects of interest (the sample means).</p><p>Based on a combination of theo=
retical expansions and extensive simulations, we have determined that, when=
 the effect entering into the definition of <i>Q</i> is the log odds ratio,=
 the mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> (under the null hypothesis of equal odds ratios) h=
ave the following properties. 1) They each converge to the corresponding ch=
i-square moments of <i>K</i>=E2=88=921 and 2(<i>K</i>=E2=88=921) as the sam=
ple sizes increase. 2) Both moments are less than the corresponding chi-squ=
are moments. That is, the =E2=80=98corrections=E2=80=99 are negative rather=
 than positive as for <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>SM</i>
                  </sub>. 3) The variance is not only less than the chi-squ=
are variance, it is less than twice the mean. 4) The moments depend on nuis=
ance parameters, which are not independent of the effects.</p><p>The two pl=
ots of Figure <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-=
action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/=
s12874-015-0034-x#Fig1">1</a> show the relation of the variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> to its mean for a representative set of simulation=
s. (See Appendix <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-tra=
ck-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1=
186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec12">Appendix A: Information about the simulations<=
/a> for a complete description of the simulations conducted). The two plots=
 have identical data, but the points are colored according to the value of =
<i>N</i> in the left plot and according to the value of <i>K</i> in the rig=
ht plot. The mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> have been divided by <i>K</i>=E2=88=921 in order t=
o place the data on the same scale. The main message of the right plot (and=
 a key finding of our simulations) is that this re-scaling is effective=E2=
=80=94the different values of <i>K</i> (5, 10, 20 and 40) are fairly unifor=
mly distributed throughout the plot, indicating that after this re-scaling =
the moments of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> have little dependence on the number of studies.
</p><div class=3D"c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-=
item" data-test=3D"figure" data-container-section=3D"figure" id=3D"figure-1=
