                        <p>In the plots, we see that the mean of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> is less than <i>K</i>=E2=88=921, that the variance=
 of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> is less than 2(<i>K</i>=E2=88=921), and that the v=
ariance is less than twice the mean. We also see in the left plot that the =
departure of the mean and variance from the chi-square values of <i>K</i>=
=E2=88=921 and 2(<i>K</i>=E2=88=921) (that is, the =E2=80=98corrections=E2=
=80=99) are greater for the study size <i>N</i>=3D90 (i.e., 45 in each arm)=
 than for the study size <i>N</i>=3D150. It is not evident from the graphs,=
 but the =E2=80=98corrections=E2=80=99 needed are also greater when the bin=
omial probabilities <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>T</i>
                  </sub> and <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub> are more distant from the central value of 1/2.</p=
><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading" id=3D"Sec5">Estimating the moments an=
d distribution of <b><i>Q</i></b>
                           <sub>
                    <b><i>LOR</i></b>
                  </sub>
                        </h3><p>In this section, we outline a method for es=
timating the mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>. The method involves fairly complicated formulas, =
but in the <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-act=
ion=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s1=
2874-015-0034-x#Sec11">Appendix</a> we provide more details and a link to a=
 program in R for carrying out the calculations.</p><p>Kulinskaya et al. [<=
a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-la=
bel=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 10" title=
=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. On the moments of C=
ochran=E2=80=99s Q statistic under the null hypothesis, with application to=
 the meta-analysis of risk difference. Res Synth Methods. 2011; 2:254=E2=80=
=9370.=20
                    doi:10.1002/jrsm.54
                   =20
                 =20
                        " href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186=
/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR10" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e3300">10</a>]=
 presented a very general expansion for the mean of <i>Q</i> for arbitrary =
effect measures in terms of the first four central moments of the effect an=
d nuisance parameters as well as the weight function expressed in terms of =
these parameters.</p><p>Necessary formulas for the application of this expa=
nsion to the first moment of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> can be found in <a data-track=3D"click" data-track=
-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.s=
pringer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec15">B.2 Information about =
formulas for mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                              <sub>
                      <i>LOR</i>
                    </sub>
                           </a>. The resulting expansion provides an approx=
imation to the mean of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>, which we will denote E<sub>
                    <i>th</i>
                  </sub>[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>] where the subscript =E2=80=98<i>th</i>=E2=80=99 i=
ndicates that this expectation is entirely theoretical. It depends on the n=
umber of studies <i>K</i>, the sample sizes of the separate arms of the stu=
dies, the estimated values of the nuisance parameters <span class=3D"mathja=
x-tex">\(\widehat {\zeta }_{i}\)</span>, the values of the estimated weight=
s and the estimated value of the effect <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\wide=
hat {\theta }\)</span> under the null hypothesis.</p><p>When we compared E<=
sub>
                    <i>th</i>
                  </sub>[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>] with the simulated values for the mean of <i>Q</i=
>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>, we found that it does an excellent job of identif=
ying the situations where =E2=80=98corrections=E2=80=99 are needed to the c=
hi-square moment, but that it over-estimates the size of the =E2=80=98corre=
ction=E2=80=99 by a constant percentage of slightly more than 1/3 (<i>R</i>
                           <sup>2</sup>=3D97.0<i>%</i>). More precisely, de=
noting the mean of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> by E[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>], we have the relation=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ6" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$ (K-1)-\text{E}[Q_{LOR}]=
=3D 0.687[(K-1)-\text{E}_{th}[Q_{LOR}]].   $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-=
article-equation__number">
                    ((6))
                </div></div>
                        <p>Although this equation is based partly on theore=
tical calculations and partly on the results of simulations (the =E2=80=9C0=
.687=E2=80=9D factor), we note that after deciding on the use of the =E2=80=
=9C0.687=E2=80=9D factor we conducted new simulations to verify that it was=
 not just a random consequence of the original simulations. More details on=
 our simulations for this formula can be found in <a data-track=3D"click" d=
ata-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https=
://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec14">B.1 Additiona=
l graphs for accuracy of level and for power</a>.</p><p>Kulinskaya et al. [=
<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-l=
abel=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 10" title=
=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. On the moments of C=
ochran=E2=80=99s Q statistic under the null hypothesis, with application to=
 the meta-analysis of risk difference. Res Synth Methods. 2011; 2:254=E2=80=
=9370.=20
                    doi:10.1002/jrsm.54
                   =20
                 =20
                        " href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186=
/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR10" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e3601">10</a>]=
 also deduced a very general theoretical expansion for the second moment of=
 <i>Q</i>, but when we applied this expansion to <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> and compared it to our simulations, we found that =
the expansion is much too inaccurate to be of any use. We conjecture that t=
his inaccuracy is due to non-uniform convergence of the expansions with res=
pect to both the number of studies <i>K</i> and the values of the binomial =
parameters. Accordingly we have chosen to estimate the variance of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> using a quadratic regression formula from our simu=
lations, as seen in Figure <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link=
" data-track-action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/art=
icle/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig1">1</a>, but using more complete data th=
an shown in those plots. As in the regression for the mean of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> we fitted a formula for the variance and then chec=
ked it against additional simulations (See the <a data-track=3D"click" data=
-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://=
link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec15">B.2 Information =
about formulas for mean and variance of <i>Q</i>
                              <sub>
                      <i>LOR</i>
                    </sub>
                           </a> for more details on our procedures). Our fo=
rmula for estimating Var[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>] is=20
</p><div id=3D"Equ7" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$ \begin{aligned} \text{Var=
}[Q_{LOR}]=3D&amp;\, 4.74(K-1) -12.17 \text{E}[Q_{LOR}]\\ &amp;+9.42\text{E=
}[Q_{LOR}]^{2}/(K-1) \end{aligned}   $$ </span></div><div class=3D"c-articl=
e-equation__number">
                    ((7))
                </div></div>
                        <p>The quadratic regression fit, using 487 of our m=
ore than 1400 simulations, had an <i>R</i>
                           <sup>2</sup> value of 98.5%. In using this equat=
ion, we first need to calculate E[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>] using Equation <a data-track=3D"click" data-track=
-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"equation anchor" href=3D"https://link.=
springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Equ6">6</a>. This quadratic =
regression is depicted by the black curve on the plot (b) of Figure <a data=
-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"figure anch=
or" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig=
1">1</a>.</p><p>Although we do not have a theoretical justification for usi=
ng a quadratic relation between the mean and variance of <i>Q</i>, such a f=
unctional relation between the mean and the variance of <i>Q</i> is often f=
ound under various conditions. For examples, in the asymptotic chi-square d=
istribution of <i>Q</i>, the variance (twice the mean) is a linear function=
 of the mean; and in the normally distributed sample mean situation of Equa=
tions (<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=
=3D"equation anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s128=
74-015-0034-x#Equ4">4</a>) and (<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D=
"link" data-track-action=3D"equation anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.=
com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Equ5">5</a>), a little algebra shows =
that again the variance is a linear function of the mean. Further, in a com=
mon one-way random effects model, Biggerstaff and Tweedie [<a data-track=3D=
"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" da=
ta-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 13" title=3D"Biggerstaff B=
J, Tweedie RL. Incorporating variability in estimates of heterogeneity in t=
he random effects model in meta-analysis. Stat Med. 1997; 16:753=E2=80=9368=
." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-=
CR13" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e3853">13</a>] show that the variance=
 of <i>Q</i> is a quadratic function of the mean.</p><p>Our simulations sho=
w that the family of gamma distributions fits the distribution of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> quite well. By matching the mean and variance of <=
i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> with the mean and variance of a gamma distribution=
, we arrive at an approximation for the distribution of <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> which can be used to conduct a test of homogeneity=
 for the equality of log odds ratios using <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub> as the test statistic. (The shape parameter <i>=CE=
=B1</i> of the gamma distribution is estimated by <i>=CE=B1</i>=3DE[<i>Q</i=
>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>]<sup>2</sup>/Var[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>], and the scale parameter <i>=CE=B2</i> is estimat=
ed by <i>=CE=B2</i>=3DVar[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>]/E[<i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>LOR</i>
                  </sub>].) The accuracy of this test statistic and a compa=
rison with other test statistics are discussed in the next section.</p></di=
v></div></section><section data-title=3D"Results and discussion"><div class=
=3D"c-article-section" id=3D"Sec6-section"><h2 class=3D"c-article-section__=
title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id=3D"Sec6">Re=
sults and discussion</h2><div class=3D"c-article-section__content" id=3D"Se=
c6-content"><h3 class=3D"c-article__sub-heading" id=3D"Sec7">Accuracy of th=
e level of the homogeneity test</h3><p>In this section we present the resul=
ts of extensive simulations designed to analyze the accuracy of the levels =
of the test of homogeneity of log odds ratios using the <i>Q</i> statistic =
together with the gamma distribution estimated from the data by the methods=
 of Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data=
-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/=
10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec5">Estimating the moments and distribution of =
<b><i>Q</i></b>
                              <sub>
                      <b><i>LOR</i></b>
                    </sub>
                           </a>=E2=80=9D. We denote this test by <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub>. The use of simulations to determine the accuracy =
of various different tests of homogeneity of log odds ratios has often been=
 discussed in the literature. See, for example, Schmidt et al. [<a data-tra=
ck=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"lin=
k" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 14" title=3D"Schmidt =
AF, Groenwold RHH, Knol MJ, Hoes AW, Nielen M, Roes KCB, et al. Exploring i=
nteraction effects in small samples increases rates of false-positive and f=
alse-negative findings: results from a systematic review and simulations st=
udy. J Clin Epidemiol. 2014; 67:821=E2=80=939." href=3D"https://link.spring=
er.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR14" id=3D"ref-link-section-d=
57159360e3988">14</a>], Bhaumik et al. [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-=
action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation=
-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 15" title=3D"Bhaumik DK, Amatya A, Normand S,=
 Greenhouse J, Kaizar E, Neelon B, et al. Meta-analysis of rare binary adve=
rse event data. J Am Stat Assoc. 2012; 107:555=E2=80=9367." href=3D"https:/=
/link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR15" id=3D"ref-li=
nk-section-d57159360e3992">15</a>], Bagheri et al. [<a data-track=3D"click"=
 data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=
=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 16" title=3D"Bagheri Z, Ayatollah=
