on-d57159360e4011">21</a>], and Jones et al. [<a data-track=3D"click" data-=
track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"ci=
tation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 22" title=3D"Jones MP, O=E2=80=99Gorman=
 TW, Lemke JH, Woolson RF. A Monte Carlo investigation of homogeneity tests=
 of odds ratio under various sample size configurations. Biometrics. 1989; =
45:171=E2=80=9381." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s1287=
4-015-0034-x#ref-CR22" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e4014">22</a>]. Our =
simulations included comparisons with some of the tests proposed by these a=
uthors. The comparisons of ours confirmed (as several of the above authors =
also discovered) that the Breslow-Day [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-a=
ction=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-=
ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 11" title=3D"Breslow NE, Day NE. Statistical m=
ethods in cancer research. Int Agency Res Cancer. 1980; 1:136=E2=80=9346." =
href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR1=
1" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e4017">11</a>] (denoted by BD) is often =
the best available among the previously considered tests.</p><p>The Breslow=
-Day test for homogeneity of odds-ratios is based on the statistic=20
</p><div id=3D"Equa" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$X^{2}_{BD}=3D\sum_{j=3D1}^=
{K}\frac{(x_{j}-X_{j}(\hat{\psi}))^{2}}{\text{Var}(x_{j}|\hat{\psi})}, $$ <=
/span></div></div><p> where <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(x_{j},\;X_{j}(\ha=
t {\psi })\)</span> and <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(\text {Var}(x_{j}|\ha=
t {\psi })\)</span> denote the observed number, the expected number and the=
 asymptotic variance of the number of events in the treatment arm of the <i=
>j</i>th study given the overall Mantel-Haenszel odds ratio <span class=3D"=
mathjax-tex">\(\hat {\psi }\)</span>, respectively. Its distribution is app=
roximated by the <i>=CF=87</i>
                           <sup>2</sup> distribution with <i>K</i>=E2=88=92=
1 degrees of freedom. We found that using the Tarone [<a data-track=3D"clic=
k" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-te=
st=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Reference 23" title=3D"Tarone RE. On hete=
rogeneity tests based on efficient scores. Biometrika. 1985; 72:91=E2=80=93=
5." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref=
-CR23" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e4338">23</a>] correction to the Bre=
slow-Day test had such small differences from BD that the two were virtuall=
y equivalent. In addition to the BD and Tarone tests, we simulated proposal=
s by Lui and Chang [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference =
anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"=
Reference 17" title=3D"Lui K-J, Chang K-C. Test homogeneity of odds ratio i=
n a randomized clinical trial with noncompliance. J Biopharmaceutical Stat.=
 2009; 19:916=E2=80=9332." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.118=
6/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR17" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e4341">17</a>=
] for testing the homogeneity of log odds ratios based on the normal approx=
imation to the distribution of the <i>z</i>-, square-root and log-transform=
ed <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>stand</i>
                  </sub> statistic. The log-transformation was also suggest=
ed by Bhaumik et al. [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"referenc=
e anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=
=3D"Reference 15" title=3D"Bhaumik DK, Amatya A, Normand S, Greenhouse J, K=
aizar E, Neelon B, et al. Meta-analysis of rare binary adverse event data. =
J Am Stat Assoc. 2012; 107:555=E2=80=9367." href=3D"https://link.springer.c=
om/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR15" id=3D"ref-link-section-d5715=
9360e4357">15</a>]. We do not report these results due to our conclusion th=
at none were superior to BD. Accordingly, in our comparative graphs below, =
we compare our <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub> test with BD and with the commonly used test (deno=
ted <span class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(Q_{\chi ^{2}}\phantom {\dot {i}\!}\)</spa=
n>), which uses the standard statistic <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>stand</i>
                  </sub> (calculated without adding 1/2 to the numbers of e=
vents when calculating log-odds) together with the chi-square distribution.=
</p><p>Our simulations for testing the null hypothesis of equal odds ratios=
 (all conducted subsequent to the adoption of the regressions of Equations =
<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"equa=
tion anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0=
034-x#Equ6">6</a> and <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" dat=
a-track-action=3D"equation anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/articl=
e/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Equ7">7</a>) are of two types. For the first ty=
pe, the parameters of all studies are identical; these simulations include =
the following parameters: number of studies <i>K</i>=3D 5, 10, 20 and 40; t=
otal study sizes <i>N</i>=3D 90, 150, and 210; proportion of the study size=
 in the control arm <i>q</i>=3D 1/3, 1/2, 2/3; null hypothesis value of the=
 log odds ratio <i>=CE=B8</i>=3D 0, 0.5, 1, 1.5, 2, and 3; and the log odds=
 of the control arm <i>=CE=B6</i>=3D =E2=80=932.2 (<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
