                        <p>Note that the power for both BD and <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub> are almost always higher than for <span class=3D"m=
athjax-tex">\(Q_{\chi ^{2}}\phantom {\dot {i}\!}\)</span>, with the differe=
nce being especially pronounced for <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.1. The inferiority of <span class=3D"mathjax-t=
ex">\(Q_{\chi ^{2}}\phantom {\dot {i}\!}\)</span> is due to its conservativ=
eness noted in the Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-labe=
l=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://link.spring=
er.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec7">Accuracy of the level of the=
 homogeneity test</a>=E2=80=9D. There is no clear-cut winner between the BD=
 and the <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub>, with BD slightly better for some situations, but =
slightly worse for others. In the three right graphs, when <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.4, we see that all three tests perform equally=
 well.</p><p>The second panel of graphs (see Figure <a data-track=3D"click"=
 data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"http=
s://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig5">5</a>) shows =
the power for the three tests when <i>=CE=B8</i>=3D3. The power of the <spa=
n class=3D"mathjax-tex">\(Q_{\chi ^{2}}\phantom {\dot {i}\!}\)</span> test =
is still the lowest of the three tests. But here the power of the <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub> test appears to be somewhat higher then for the BD=
 when <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.1, about the same when <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.2, and noticeably lower in the extreme situati=
on when <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.4. These differences in power between the BD a=
nd <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub> tests are both the consequences of the fact that t=
he <i>Q</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>=CE=B3</i>
                  </sub> test is somewhat liberal for <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.1 and somewhat conservative for <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D0.4, as can be seen from Figure <a data-track=3D=
"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"figure anchor" href=
=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig2">2</a>=
. The BD test is the closest to the nominal level in these circumstances.
