v>
                        <p>The value of Cochran=E2=80=99s <i>Q</i> statisti=
c is 25.023. The standard chi-square approximation with 16 df yields the p-=
value of 0.069 for the test for homogeneity. The estimated mean E<sub>
                    <i>th</i>
                  </sub>[<i>Q</i>] of the null distribution of <i>Q</i> is =
14.18 and the corrected mean using Equation <a data-track=3D"click" data-tr=
ack-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"equation anchor" href=3D"https://li=
nk.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Equ6">6</a> is E[<i>Q</i>=
]=3D14.75. The estimated variance calculated from Equation <a data-track=3D=
"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"equation anchor" hre=
f=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Equ7">7</a=
> is 24.43. The parameters of the approximating gamma distribution are <i>=
=CE=B1</i>=3D8.90 and <i>=CE=B2</i>=3D1.66. The p-value using this gamma di=
stribution is 0.037. The Breslow-Day statistic value is 26.22 and the p-val=
ue is 0.051; the Tarone correction provides the same values to 4 decimal pl=
aces. To evaluate the correctness of these p-values, we simulated one milli=
on values of <i>Q</i> from the fixed null distribution with each study havi=
ng the null value <i>=CE=B8</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>w</i>
                  </sub>=3D1.58 for the odds ratio together with the origin=
al individual values for the control parameters <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>Ci</i>
                  </sub>. The conclusion, based on the empirical results, i=
s that the p-value should be 0.0330. Thus for this example, the gamma distr=
ibution result is closest to that given by the simulations and the standard=
 chi-square value is furthest.</p><p>The most current version of the review=
 (Update 4) contains only one more trial by Unrod (2007) for this compariso=
n. The values are event<sub>
                    <i>T</i>
                  </sub>=3D28, event<sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D18, <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>T</i>
                  </sub>=3D237, <i>n</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D228. With the addition of these data, the test o=
f heterogeneity results in <i>Q</i>=3D25.023, and the p-value of 0.094 is o=
btained by the standard chi-square approximation with 17 df. Our method res=
ults in E<sub>
                    <i>th</i>
                  </sub>[<i>Q</i>]=3D15.14, and the corrected value E[<i>Q<=
/i>]=3D15.72, Var[<i>Q</i>]=3D26.22, with the gamma distribution parameters=
 <i>=CE=B1</i>=3D9.43 and <i>=CE=B2</i>=3D1.67. The p-value from the gamma =
approximation is 0.055. The BD test statistic is 26.22 and its p-value is 0=
.071; the Tarone correction, once more, results in the same values to 4 dec=
imal places. Another set of one million simulations from the null distribut=
ion yielded the empirical p-value of 0.0497.</p><p>For the data in these tw=
o examples, the gamma approximation results in lower and more accurate p-va=
lues than the p-values of both the standard chi-square approximation and th=
e Breslow-Day test. However, in our more extensive simulations there were c=
ases in which the Breslow-Day test was superior. Note that this example has=
 fairly low numbers of events (between 1% and 5% for many studies), which, =
as mentioned at the end of Section =E2=80=9C<a data-track=3D"click" data-tr=
ack-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"section anchor" href=3D"https://lin=
k.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Sec7">Accuracy of the leve=
l of the homogeneity test</a>=E2=80=9D, is a situation where the Breslow-Da=
y test may struggle.</p><p>Figures <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=
=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer=
.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig7">7</a> and <a data-track=3D"cli=
ck" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"h=
ttps://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig8">8</a> prov=
ide a comparison which indicates the excellence of the fit of our gamma app=
roximation to the entire distribution of <i>Q</i> and the poor fit of the c=
hi-square approximation. Using the data of Stead et al. with 17 studies, we=
 simulated 10,000 values of <i>Q</i> to provide an empirical distribution o=
f <i>Q</i>. Figure <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-t=
rack-action=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.=
1186/s12874-015-0034-x#Fig7">7</a> shows the fit of our estimated gamma dis=
tribution (<i>=CE=B1</i>=3D8.90 and <i>=CE=B2</i>=3D1.66). Note that the fi=
t is quite good throughout the entire empirical distribution. On the other =
hand, Figure <a data-track=3D"click" data-track-label=3D"link" data-track-a=
ction=3D"figure anchor" href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s=
12874-015-0034-x#Fig8">8</a> shows that the empirical distribution of <i>Q<=
/i> departs substantially from the chi-square distribution with 16 df, agai=
n throughout the entire distribution.
