ce 29" title=3D"DerSimonian R, Kacker R. Random-effects model for meta-anal=
ysis of clinical trials: An update. Contemporary Clin Trials. 2007; 28:105=
=E2=80=9314." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-=
0034-x#ref-CR29" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e6445">29</a>] methods use=
 the first moment (<i>K</i>=E2=88=921) and the chi-square percentiles appli=
ed to the distribution of <i>Q</i> to provide, respectively, point and inte=
rval estimation of <i>=CF=84</i>
                        <sup>2</sup>. The latter is achieved through =E2=80=
=98profiling=E2=80=99 the distribution of <i>Q</i>, i.e., inverting the <i>=
Q</i> test (see Viechtbauer [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"r=
eference anchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-=
label=3D"Reference 27" title=3D"Viechtbauer W. Confidence intervals for the=
 amount of heterogeneity in meta-analysis. Stat Med. 2007; 26:37=E2=80=9352=
." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-=
CR27" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e6466">27</a>]). From our previous wo=
rk with Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l on the homogeneity test for standardized mean =
differences [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference anchor"=
 data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"Referen=
ce 9" title=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. Testing =
for homogeneity in meta-analysis I, The one parameter case: Standardized me=
an difference. Biometrics. 2011; 67:203=E2=80=9312. doi:10.1111/j.1541-0420=
.2010.01442.x." href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-01=
5-0034-x#ref-CR9" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e6469">9</a>] and for the=
 risk differences [<a data-track=3D"click" data-track-action=3D"reference a=
nchor" data-track-label=3D"link" data-test=3D"citation-ref" aria-label=3D"R=
eference 10" title=3D"Kulinskaya E, Dollinger MB, Bj=C3=B8rkest=C3=B8l K. O=
n the moments of Cochran=E2=80=99s Q statistic under the null hypothesis, w=
ith application to the meta-analysis of risk difference. Res Synth Methods.=
 2011; 2:254=E2=80=9370.=20
                    doi:10.1002/jrsm.54
                   =20
                 =20
                        " href=3D"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186=
/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR10" id=3D"ref-link-section-d57159360e6472">10</a>]=
, it is clear that the non-asymptotic distribution of <i>Q</i> strongly dep=
ends on the effect of interest. This conclusion is confirmed here for <i>Q<=
/i> when the effects are log odds ratios. The use of the correct moments an=
d improved approximations to the distribution of <i>Q</i> for the point and=
 interval estimation of <i>=CF=84</i>
                        <sup>2</sup> for a variety of different effect meas=
ures may provide greatly improved estimators, especially for small values o=
f heterogeneity and will be the subject of our further work.</p></div></div=
