i>K</i>=3D40, unless stated otherwise. The set of simulations with all stud=
ies having identical parameters were as follows: study size <i>N</i>=3D 90,=
 150 and 210; proportion of each study in the control arm <i>q</i> =3D 1/2,=
 1/3 and 2/3; log odds ratio (null hypothesis) <i>=CE=B8</i>=3D 0, 0.5, 1.0=
, 1.5, 2.0 and 3.0; and binomial probabilities in the control arm <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>=3D 0.1, 0.2 and 0.4. It is easier and more intuiti=
ve to select values of <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub> than to select values of the actual nuisance param=
eter <i>=CE=B6</i>=3D log(<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>)=E2=88=92 log(1=E2=88=92<i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub>).</p><p>For the simulations using unequal paramete=
rs among the various studies, the parameter choices can be described as fol=
lows. For <i>K</i>=3D5, we use three vectors of study sizes: &lt;<i>N</i>&g=
t;=3D&lt;36,48,54,60,252&gt;; &lt;96,108,114,120,312&gt;; and &lt;163,173,1=
78,184,352&gt;. These three vectors have average study sizes 90, 150 and 21=
0 respectively, which corresponds to the study sizes of the equal simulatio=
ns. The null hypothesis values of the log odds ratio <i>=CE=B8</i> are 0, 0=
.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2 and 3. For each fixed value of <i>=CE=B8</i>, we chose five=
 values of <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>C</i>
                  </sub> with the goal of keeping <i>p</i>
                           <sub>
                    <i>T</i>
                  </sub> away from 1.0 (see below for these values). Denote=
 the vector of these values of <i>p</i>
