ink.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12874-015-0034-x#ref-CR12" id=3D"ref-link=
-section-d57159360e9745">12</a>]. However, instead of using the approximati=
ons for the central moments given by Gart et al., our R-program calculates =
these exactly.</p><p>The derivation of the expansion is a straightforward a=
pplication of the delta method in which <i>Q</i> is first expanded in a mul=
tivariate Taylor series centered at the null hypothesis and then expectatio=
ns are taken of the resulting expansion, keeping only those terms of order =
<i>O</i>(1) and <i>O</i>(1/<i>n</i>). For the Taylor expansion of <i>Q</i>,=
 we consider <i>Q</i> as a function of the estimators of the effect and nui=
sance parameters as follows:=20
</p><div id=3D"Equc" class=3D"c-article-equation"><div class=3D"c-article-e=
quation__content"><span class=3D"mathjax-tex"> $$\begin{array}{@{}rcl@{}} Q=
&amp;=3D&amp;\sum_{i}\widehat{w}_{i}(\widehat{\theta}_{i}-\widehat{\theta}_=
{w})^{2}=3D Q[\widehat{\theta}_{1},\ldots,\widehat{\theta}_{K}, \widehat{w}=
_{1},\ldots,\widehat{w}_{K}]\\[-3pt] &amp;=3D&amp;Q[\widehat{\theta}_{1},\l=
dots,\widehat{\theta}_{K}, f_{1}(\widehat{\theta}_{1},\widehat{\zeta}_{1}),=
\ldots, f_{K}(\widehat{\theta}_{K},\widehat{\zeta}_{K})]. \end{array} $$ </=
span></div></div>
